{"id":"2011.00199","submitter":"Longwen Zhou","authors":"Longwen Zhou and Qianqian Du","title":"Floquet dynamical quantum phase transitions in periodically quenched\n  systems","comments":"12pages, 6 figures, close to the published version","journal-ref":"J. Phys.: Condens. Matter 33 345403 (2021)","doi":"10.1088/1361-648X/ac0b60","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Dynamical quantum phase transitions (DQPTs) are characterized by nonanalytic\nbehaviors of physical observables as functions of time. When a system is\nsubject to time-periodic modulations, the nonanalytic signatures of its\nobservables could recur periodically in time, leading to the phenomena of\nFloquet DQPTs. In this work, we systematically explore Floquet DQPTs in a class\nof periodically quenched one-dimensional system with chiral symmetry. By tuning\nthe strength of quench, we find multiple Floquet DQPTs within a single driving\nperiod, with more DQPTs being observed when the system is initialized in\nFloquet states with larger topological invariants. Each Floquet DQPT is further\naccompanied by the quantized jump of a dynamical topological order parameter,\nwhose values remain quantized in time if the underlying Floquet system is\nprepared in a gapped topological phase. The theory is demonstrated in a\npiecewise quenched lattice model, which possesses rich Floquet topological\nphases and is readily realizable in quantum simulators like the\nnitrogen-vacancy center in diamonds. Our discoveries thus open a new\nperspective for the Floquet engineering of DQPTs and the dynamical detection of\ntopological phase transitions in Floquet systems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 31 Oct 2020 06:19:31 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 1 Jul 2021 10:20:12 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-07-02"}
